Artificial Neural Networks > Fitting¶

Alpio Jorge

May 2021

Training ANN > summary¶

  • Also called fitting or learning
    • The parameters to learn are the weights
    • The number of parameters can be large
    • The relationship between the data and the parameters is complex
    • There is no analytical solution (in general)
    • We need a search procedure

Training ANN¶

  • The loss function to minimize:
    • SSE - sum of squared errors, for regression
    • Cross-Entropy, for classification
  • To avoid overfitting some regularization is used
    • we can penalize more or less the magnitude of the weights
  • The generic search approach is gradient based
    • In the case of ANN, some kind of backpropagation

Simple intuitive example¶

  • Before going into backropagation
    • How to train a perceptron?
  • Raw implementation with numpy
    • Weights $w$
    • Point $x$
    • True class $y$
    • Step function
In [250]:
import numpy as np

x=np.array([1,-0.5,0])
w=np.array([-0.1,0.1,0.1])
y=1

def step(x):
    if x>=0: 
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

yhat = step(sum(w*x))
print("y =",y,", yhat =", yhat, ", w.x =", sum(w*x))

y = 1 , yhat = 0 , w.x = -0.15000000000000002

Updating the parameters¶

  • Current $w$ gives a wrong answer to $x$
  • We have to change $w$
    • the prediction needs to get closer to the true class
  • $\hat{y} = step(w.x)$
  • $w$ and $x$ are vectors
  • $w.x$ is their inner product
    • it is 0 when $w$ and $x$ are orthogonal
    • it is positive when they are minimally aligned (less than $90^{\circ}$)
    • it is negative when they are not aligned (more than $90^{\circ}$)
  • In the example:
    • True class is $1$, prediction is $0$
    • So, we want to make $w$ more aligned with $x$
    • One way is to add $x$ to $w$
      • $w_{new}=w+x$
    • $w_{new}.x=(w+x).x=w.x+x.x \ge w.x$ because $x.x$ is always positive
    • So, $step(w_{new}.x)$ is closer to $1$
  • What have we done?
    • We got a rule to update $w$ when we have a wrong answer for class 1
In [251]:
# update w

w=np.array([-0.1,0.1,0.1])
print("w =",w)
w = w + x
print("wnew =",w)
print("wnew.x =", sum(w*x))
print("yhat =",step(sum(w*x)))

w = [-0.1  0.1  0.1]
wnew = [ 0.9 -0.4  0.1]
wnew.x = 1.1
yhat = 1

The case of class 0¶

  • If the true class is 0
    • We need $w.x$ to be negative
    • So, we make $w$ and $x$ less aligned
    • We decrease $w.x$
      • $w_{new}=w-x$
    • $w_{new}.x=(w-x).x=w.x-x.x \le w.x$ because $x.x$ is always positive
    • So, $step(w_{new}.x)$ is closer to $0$
  • Let us now take a small dataset of size 5

Predict and error¶

  • We define
    • predict, which takes matrices
    • total_error, which computes classification error
In [254]:
def predict(X,w):
    return np.array(list(map(lambda x: step(sum(w*x)),X)))

def total_error(X,y,w):
    return 1-sum((predict(X,w)==y)*1.0)/len(y)

print("y =",y)
print("yhat =", predict(X,w))
print("Error =", total_error(X,y,w))

y = [1 1 1 0 0]
yhat = [1 1 1 1 1]
Error = 0.4

Fitting¶

  • Fitting algorithm:
    • Consider one example at a time
    • Predict a class with the current $w$
    • Compare with true class
    • If the answer is correct do nothing
    • Otherwise:
      • If true class $1$ make $w$ more aligned with $x$
      • If true class $0$ make $w$ less aligned with $x$
    • We can repeat the process for a number of epochs
    • Or until it converges
In [257]:
w=np.array([-0.1,-0.1,-0.1])
y=np.array([1,1,1,0,0])

def fit(X,y,w):
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        x=X[i:(i+1),:]
        yhat=predict(x,w)[0]
        yhat
        if y[i]==1 and yhat==0:
            w=w+X[i]
        elif y[i]==0 and yhat==1:
            w=w-X[i]
    return w
            
print(w)
print(y)
print(predict(X,w))
print(total_error(X,y,w))

epochs=20

for i in range(epochs):
    w=fit(X,y,w)

print(w)
print(y)
print(predict(X,w))
print(total_error(X,y,w))

Fitting¶

  • The algorithm converges
    • This can be proved
  • The initial $w$ is arbitrary
    • Can be random with small values around 0
    • Different initial values may make fitting more or less easy
  • Example: Apply to a larger artificial dataset
    • With a clean linear separation

from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

cmap_bg='Pastel1'
cmap_fg='Set1'

def plot_classifier_boundary(model,X,h = .05):
    # this function can be used with any sklearn classifier
    # ready for two classes but can be easily extended
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min()-.2, X[:, 0].max()+.2
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min()-.2, X[:, 1].max()+.2
    # generate a grid with step h
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                         np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
    # the method ravel flattens xx and yy
    Z = model.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap=cmap_bg)
    plt.xlim((x_min,x_max))
    plt.ylim((y_min,y_max))
    
n_points=100
std1=2
std2=1

X,y = make_blobs(n_samples=[n_points*2], centers=[(0,0)], 
                 n_features=2, cluster_std=[std1],
                 random_state=1, shuffle=False)

y[X[:,0]+X[:,1]>0]=1

# define a sklearn-like class for home made perceptron
class hmper:
    def __init__(self,weights=0,bias=1,n_epochs=10,learning_rate=1):
        self.w=weights
        self.bias=bias
        self.epochs=n_epochs
        self.lr=learning_rate
    def predict(self,X):
        return np.array(list(map(
            lambda x: step(sum(self.w*x)+self.bias),
            X)))
    def fit(self,X,y):
        lr=self.lr
        for i in range(self.epochs):
            for i in range(X.shape[0]):
                x=X[i:(i+1),:]
                yhat=self.predict(x)[0]
                if y[i]==1 and yhat==0:
                    self.w=self.w+lr*X[i]
                    self.bias=self.bias+lr
                elif y[i]==0 and yhat==1:
                    self.w=self.w-lr*X[i]
                    self.bias=self.bias-lr

        
w=np.array([0.1,-0.1])

model=hmper(weights=w, n_epochs=20)
model.fit(X,y)

plot_classifier_boundary(model,X)

plt.scatter(X[:,0],X[:,1],c=y,cmap=cmap_fg)
plt.title('Home made perceptron')
plt.xlabel('$x_1$')
plt.ylabel('$x_2$');

Fitting the perceptron > summary¶

  • Start with random / arbitrary weights
  • Compare prediction with true value
  • Iteratively update weights to improve solution
    • In the perceptron: by changing the angle between $w$ and each $x_i$
  • A general approach for weight updating is based on gradients
    • Define a loss function with respect to the parameters
    • Minimize the loss by following the gradient

MLP for Regression > 1 hidden layer¶

  • Let us now consider MLP
  • Prediction is feedforward
    • Calculate each hidden node value $Z_m$ from inputs $X$ $$ Z_m = h_m(X) = \sigma ( \alpha_{0m} + \alpha_m^T X) , m = 1 , . . . , M $$
    • And then each output layer node $T_k$ from the $Z$
$$ T_k =\beta_{0k} + \beta_k^T Z, k=1,...,K$$$$ f_k(X) = g_k(h(X)) $$

Fitting MLP¶

  • A MLP defines a function $f(x; w)$
  • To find $w$ we use an optimization approach
    • Define error
    • Derivate error
    • Use a gradient based approach
  • The function $f(x)$ is not easy to derivate w.r.t. $w$ in one go
    • Because of the multiple layers
  • Fortunately we can decompose the derivative of $f(x;w)$
    • One simple derivative per layer
    • First we work with the output layer
    • And go backwards, layer by layer
    • This is the general idea of the Backpropagation Algorithm

Fitting MLP¶

  • The backpropagation algorithm (high level)
    • Predict the output for the inputs using the current weights
      • Feedforward
    • Compute the errors for the output node(s) given the true values
    • Backpropagate (distribute) these errors to the hidden layer
      • Weights are important

Fitting MLP¶

  • To derive the update expressions (single output regression):
    • minimize $R(\alpha,\beta)= \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{2}(f(x_i; \alpha,\beta) - y_i)^2$
    • To minimize, we use a gradient based approach
    • find derivatives of $R$ w.r.t. $\alpha$ and $\beta$
  • Obtain (1 hidden layer):
$$ \beta_{km}^{(r+1)}=\beta_{km}^{(r)} - \gamma_r \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \beta_{km}^{(r)}} $$$$ \alpha_{ml}^{(r+1)}=\alpha_{ml}^{(r)} - \gamma_r \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \alpha_{ml}^{(r)}} $$
  • $\gamma$ is the learning rate
  • $r$ is the epoch
  • $k$ spans over the output nodes
  • $l$ spans over the input nodes
  • $m$ spans over the hidden nodes

Backpropagation in more detail¶

  • Assuming the quadratic loss, no bias and identity activation
    • Let us take care of the output layer
    • Note: this is a sketch
  • $R(\beta)= \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{2}(g(z_i; \beta) - y_i)^2$
    • $R$ is total output error,
    • $i$ spans over examples,
    • $g$ gives output from hidden nodes, $g(z)=f(x) = g(h(x))$
  • $R(\beta)= \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{2}(\beta.z_i - y_i)^2$
    • $g$ is the identity function on inner product
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \beta} = -z_i.y_i +z_i.z_i \beta$
    • obtain the square and derivate
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \beta} = z_i(z_i \beta -y_i)$
    • isolate $z_i$
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \beta} = z_i Err_i$
  • Update rule
    • Move the parameter vector in the opposite direction of the gradient
      • Shorten the update step with the learning rate $\gamma$
    • $\beta_{new} = \beta - \gamma z_i Err_i$
  • Remember the perceptron?
    • Perceptron only has 1 layer ($z_i=x_i$)
    • $Err_i = 1$ and $\gamma = 1$ and we see the resemblance
    • Note, however, that this is regression, and the perceptron was a classifier

More than 1 layer¶

  • What happens if we have 1 hidden layer?
  • Consider the case $x_i$ (a vector)
    • $\hat{y}_i = t_i = f(x_i) = g(h(x_i)) = g(z_i)$
    • $= \sum_m \beta_m z_{im}$
    • $= \beta z_i$
    • $= \sum_m \beta~ A(a_m)$
  • To obtain $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \alpha_{m}}$
    • Use the chain rule
      • $(g(h(x))' = g'(h(x)).h'(x)$
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \alpha_{m}} = \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial a_m} \frac{\partial a_m}{\partial \alpha_m}$, with $a_m = \sum_l \alpha_{lm}.x_{il}$
  • We now call the first term $\delta_{mi}$ (the error)
    • $\delta_{mi} = \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial a_m}$
  • The second term can be obtained as
    • $\frac{\partial a_m}{\partial \alpha_m} = \frac{\partial \sum_l \alpha_{lm}.x_{il}}{\partial \alpha_m} = \sum_l x_{il} = x_i$

  • We can now represent the derivative in terms of error and input

  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \alpha_{m}} = \delta_{m i} x_i$

The output layer¶

  • What is the error of the output node (we assume 1 node)?
    • The derivative of $R$ w.r.t. the activation value
  • $\delta_{oi} = \frac{\partial \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{2}(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}{\partial \hat{y}_i}$
  • $\delta_{oi} = (\hat{y}_i - y_i)$

The hidden layer¶

  • $\delta_{\alpha i} = \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial a_m}$
  • We apply the chain rule again
    • This is where the magic happens
  • $\delta_{\alpha i} = \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \hat{y}_i} \frac{\partial \hat{y}_i}{\partial a_m}$
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \hat{y}_i} = \delta_{oi} = (\hat{y}_i-y_i)$
  • $\hat{y}_i = \sum_m \beta_m.A(a_m)$
  • $\frac{\partial \hat{y}_i}{\partial a_m} = \sum_m \beta_m A'(a_m)$
  • $\delta_{mi} = \delta_{oi} \beta_m A'(a_m) $
    • Final error is distributed through nidden nodes
  • The final step is to obtain the gradient for the hidden layer
  • $\frac{\partial R_i}{\partial \alpha_{m}} = \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial a_m} \frac{\partial a_m}{\partial \alpha_m}$
  • $= \delta_{mi} . x_i = \delta_{oi} \beta_m A'(a_m) . x_i$
  • $\Delta Err_{mi} = \delta_{oi} \beta_m A'(a_m)$
  • $= \delta_{oi} \beta_m A(a_m)(1-A(a_m))$
  • Update rule for the hidden layer
    • $\alpha_m = \alpha_m - \gamma \Delta Err_{mi} . x_i$

Example¶

  • Example (adapted from Han et al.)
    • $x=(1,0,1)$, $o_6=0.474$, $T=1$,
    • $Err_6=0.474-1=-0.526$
  • Given values of $o_4$ and $w_{46}$
    • $o_4=0.332$,
    • $w_{46}=-0.3$
  • Update $w_{46}$
    • $w_{46} = -0.3 - (0.9)(0.332)(-0.526)= -0.1428$
  • Calculate error in unit 4 backpropagating error in 6
    • $\Delta Err_4=Err_6 . w_{46} . A'(o_4)$
    • $\Delta Err_4=(-0.526)(-0.3)((1-0.332)(0.332)) = 0.0350$

Updating weights¶

  • Calculate the delta of $w$
$$ \Delta w_{ij}=\gamma. \Delta Err_j. o_i $$
  • Given
    • $\gamma = 0.9$
    • $o_1=x_1=1$
  • $\Delta w_{14}=(0.9)(0.0350)(1)= 0.0315$
  • Update $w$
$$w_{ij}=w_{ij} - \Delta w_{ij}$$
  • Given
    • (old) $w_{14}=0.2$
  • (new) $w_{14}=0.2 - 0.0315 = 0.1685$

Training ANN > random start¶

  • Starting values for the weights
    • Random values around zero
      • Good idea
      • Model starts linear and becomes non-linear with learning
    • Exactly zero
      • Never moves
    • Large values
      • Leads generally to poor solutions

Training ANN > overfitting¶

  • Overfitting
  • ANN have many parameters
    • overfitting can easily happen
  • To avoid overfitting stop early
    • use a validation set
    • use weight decay and minimize $R(\theta) + \lambda J(\theta)$ (regularization)
      • weights tend to zero with larger $\lambda$

Training ANN > standardization¶

  • Scaling of the inputs
    • Different variable scales imply different weight scales
      • this can have an effect on regularization
    • standardization of variables puts all on the same page
      • subtract the mean, divide by standard deviation

Training ANN > the topology¶

  • Before training we must define the topology of the network
  • Number of hidden nodes
    • More nodes make the model more flexible / expressive
      • beware of overfitting and excessive computation time
    • Too many hidden nodes can turn to zero with appropriate regularization
    • Number can be determined with cross validation
    • But one can instead use CV to determine the regularization parameter
    • Better too many than too few

Training ANN > hidden layers¶

  • Each layer extracts features (abstraction)
  • Multiple layers allow herarchical features
  • Decision depends on background knowledge and experimentation
  • More layers mean more parameters, higher computation time, more overfitting, etc.

Training ANN > complexity¶

Computational Considerations:

  • Given:
    • $N$ observations,
    • $p$ predictors,
    • $M$ hidden units and
    • $L$ training epochs,
  • Training an ANN takes typically
$$ O(NpML) $$
